## Project Soul (Read Before Every Session)

> *"This tool was built for my past self — the version of me who was learning to think about politics, war, history, and conflict with a global mental map for the first time. I hope someone in the US will open this and encounter an atrocity, a conflict, or a people they had never thought about before. I want people to learn. That is the only goal."*

---

## What This Tool Actually Is

This is not a news aggregator. It is not trying to compete with Ground News or Reuters.

It is a **curiosity engine** — designed for a curious American who doesn't follow international news and has no mental map of the world yet. The tool's job is to pull them in, orient them, give them just enough context to feel something, and then send them out to real sources to learn more.

The user arrives. They see something curated that catches their eye. They explore a map and stumble into a story they didn't know existed. They read a brief historical anchor that makes the story feel connected to something real, not random. They follow a link to a real source. They come back tomorrow.

That is the entire loop. Everything else is decoration.

---

## UX Blueprint

### Landing Experience
The homepage opens with a **persistent search bar at the top** — always visible, always accessible. This serves users who arrive with a specific story or country in mind, and serves the builder (you) when verifying that the tool is surfacing real, relevant data.

Below the search bar: a **featured story or region** — something hand-curated or algorithmically surfaced as high-relevance and underreported. Not a list. One thing, presented with enough weight to make someone stop scrolling.

Below the featured story: **the map**.

### The Map (Hero Element)
The map is a **discovery surface** — the primary way users explore, not a supporting sidebar. It should feel like a globe you can poke around. Countries with active stories are visually distinct (brighter = more coverage volume).

**Hover:** mousing over a country highlights its border and shows a minimal tooltip — the country name only. No stories yet. Just orientation.

**Click or tap:** opens a story panel with the top 3 recent stories from that country. Tap on mobile works identically to click on desktop — no separate interaction model.

Users might land on Myanmar because they clicked Southeast Asia out of curiosity, not because they searched for it. This is the moment the tool is designed for: *accidental discovery of something real.*

### Search Bar (Always Visible)
The search bar sits at the top of every page, persistently. It serves a different user than the map — the investigator rather than the explorer — and also serves as the primary tool for the builder to verify data quality.

**Search inputs:**
- Free text keyword (e.g. "coup", "famine", "election")
- Country name or region (autocomplete suggested)
- Date range (last 7 / 30 / 90 days / all time)
- Topic category (see full list below)

**Topic categories** (these are the tool's editorial taxonomy — distinct from GDELT's internal codes, which Claude Code must map to these):
- Conflict & War
- War Crimes & Genocide
- Elections & Democracy
- Economics & Trade
- Labor & Unions
- Industry & Corporate Power
- Climate & Environment
- Human Rights
- Public Health

**Important implementation note for Claude Code:** GDELT uses CAMEO event codes and GKG theme strings internally. The topic categories above are user-facing labels. Claude Code must research the GDELT taxonomy, map each category to the closest available GDELT codes or themes, document any gaps, and flag categories where GDELT coverage is thin (War Crimes and Genocide in particular may require supplementation from Wikipedia or manual curation).

**When a search is run:**
- A results panel opens alongside the map (sidebar on desktop, drawer on mobile)
- Countries matching the search results are highlighted on the map simultaneously
- The map does not disappear — it stays visible and responds to the search
- Clicking a country on the map while a search is active filters results to that country
- Clearing the search returns the map to its default discovery state

### Story Cards
Inspired by the **Ground News model** — each story shows how the same event is being covered differently across sources and countries. Not left/center/right like Ground News does it politically, but geographically: how is this story covered by local press vs. international press? What details appear in one and not the other?

Each card is a **gateway**, not a destination. Enough to spark curiosity. A clear path out to the real source.

### The Historical Anchor (Signature Feature)
Every story has a **"Background" section** — a short, neutral, factual block that answers: *why is this happening?* Not opinion. Not framing. Just: here is what led to this moment, in plain language, sourced from Wikipedia or established historical record.

This is what makes the tool different. Most news assumes you already know why Sudan matters, why the IMF is involved, why this border has been contested for 40 years. This tool never assumes that. It always explains.

### What the User Walks Away With
After 10 minutes, the user should feel: *I didn't know this was happening. I didn't know these forces were connected. I want to understand more.*

The long-term learning objective is **systems thinking** — seeing how politics, economics, industry, and power interconnect across borders. That ambition lives in the design philosophy of every feature, even if the first version only scratches the surface through the historical anchor.

### What This Tool Is NOT (Design Constraints)
- Not a real-time breaking news feed
- Not editorially opinionated — the tool presents facts, not conclusions
- Not self-contained — it always sends users to primary sources
- Not designed for people who already follow international news closely

