## Phase 2 — Map as Hero

**Goal:** Build the interactive discovery map AND the persistent search bar. These are the two primary entry points — explorer (map) and investigator (search) — and they must work together: search results highlight on the map, map clicks filter search results.

**Run this prompt:**

---

```
Read CLAUDE.md before doing anything else.

Phase 2 goal: Build the map as the hero discovery surface. This is the most important UI element in the tool.

Map requirements:
- Use Leaflet.js with OpenStreetMap tiles (free, no API key, attribution required)
- The map should fill most of the viewport — it is NOT a sidebar
- Countries with active news stories (from GDELT) should be visually highlighted
- Use a muted, serious color palette — this is not a game or a travel site. Suggested: dark navy base map, warm amber highlights for countries with stories, deeper red-amber for countries with high story volume
- Do NOT use bright or playful colors. The subject matter is serious.

STEP 2A — Base map with hover & interaction states
- Render a full-viewport world map
- Load country boundary GeoJSON (use Natural Earth free data) — this single GeoJSON layer handles ALL map interactions: hover, click, and story volume encoding. Do not create separate layers for each.
- Countries with no stories: subtle, dark, receding
- Countries with stories: highlighted in the warm amber palette
- Hover state: highlight the country border and show a simple tooltip with the country name only — no stories yet. Example: "Sudan". Keep it minimal.
- Attribution for OpenStreetMap must be visible per their requirements
- Small country tap handling: many countries (Haiti, Bahrain, Luxembourg, etc.) are hard to tap accurately on mobile. Add a small tap radius buffer (approx 10px) so users don't have to be pixel-perfect. Test this against at least 3 small countries.

STEP 2B — Click/tap to explore
- Clicking or tapping a country opens a story panel (sidebar on desktop, bottom drawer on mobile)
- Tap behavior is identical to click — no separate mobile interaction model needed
- The panel shows: country name, flag emoji, region, and the 3 most recent GDELT stories for that country
- Each story shows: headline, source, date, and a "Read more →" link to the original article
- Panel is dismissible. Clicking/tapping another country replaces it.

STEP 2C — Story count layer
- Countries should visually encode how many stories they have — not just highlighted/not highlighted
- Use opacity or color intensity to show volume: more stories = more vivid highlight
- This makes the coverage gap visible without editorializing — the map shows it, the user notices it

STEP 2D — Persistent search bar
- Add a search bar fixed to the top of the page, visible at all times
- Search inputs:
  - Free text keyword field
  - Country/region dropdown with autocomplete (populated from our GeoJSON country list — no extra API needed)
  - Date range selector: Last 7 days / Last 30 days / Last 90 days / All time
  - Topic category dropdown with these user-facing labels: Conflict & War, War Crimes & Genocide, Elections & Democracy, Economics & Trade, Labor & Unions, Industry & Corporate Power, Climate & Environment, Human Rights, Public Health
- When a search is submitted:
  - A results panel opens to the right of the map (desktop) or as a bottom drawer (mobile)
  - Countries with matching stories are highlighted on the map in addition to their default story-volume highlight
  - The panel shows results as story cards: headline, source, country, date, "Read more →"
- Clearing the search closes the panel and returns the map to default state
- Important: research how each topic category maps to GDELT's CAMEO codes or GKG themes. Document this mapping in a comment block. Flag any categories where GDELT coverage is weak and note that manual curation or Wikipedia supplementation may be needed for those.

Stop here. Show me the running map AND a working search before moving on. Test the search with at least these queries: "Sudan" (country), "election" (keyword), "Labor & Unions" (topic category), and a date range filter.
```

